         <h1>Robert Marasco, 62, Writer of 'Child's Play' </h1>
           <div class="row">
               <div class="col-md-10">
 					<p class="text-left">
<blue>1</blue>Robert Marasco , a playwright and novelist who wrote the long-running Broadway thriller '' Child 's Play , '' died on Sunday at North Shore University Hospital in Manhasset , N.Y . <br><blue>2</blue>He was 62 and lived in High Falls , N.Y . <br><blue>3</blue>He died of lung cancer , said his sister , Carole Melillo . '' <br><blue>4</blue>Child 's Play , '' an eerie melodrama about incidents of evil in a Roman Catholic boys ' school , was a surprise success in 1970 . <br><blue>5</blue>Produced by David Merrick , it ran for 343 performances . <br><blue>6</blue>Leading the cast were Fritz Weaver , Ken Howard , Pat Hingle and David Rounds . <br><blue>7</blue>Both Mr. Weaver and Mr. Howard won Tony awards , as did Joseph Hardy for his direction and Jo Mielziner for the lighting and Gothic set design . <br><blue>8</blue>Mr. Merrick subsequently produced the film version of the play , directed by Sidney Lumet and starring James Mason and Robert Preston . <br><blue>9</blue>Mr. Marasco was born in the Bronx and graduated from Regis High School in Manhattan and Fordham University . <br><blue>10</blue>He was a classical scholar and before writing the play taught Latin , Greek and English at Regis . <br><blue>11</blue>When '' Child 's Play '' was produced , he refused to reveal the name of his school because he thought that theatergoers would think the work was based on reality . <br><blue>12</blue>It was , he said , fiction . <br><blue>13</blue>In an interview , he said that the idea came from two sources : a newspaper clipping '' about a teacher who gave his kids some work to do and then jumped out of a classroom window '' and the film '' Torment '' ( written by Ingmar Bergman ) , in which there was '' a sadistic Latin teacher . '' <br><blue>14</blue>Originally titled '' The Dark , '' the play was scheduled to be directed by Harold Prince . <br><blue>15</blue>After Mr. Prince dropped his option , Mr. Merrick signed the unknown playwright . <br><blue>16</blue>When the author and his director met , Mr. Hardy asked him what his aim was in writing the play . <br><blue>17</blue>Mr. Marasco said that it was to '' scare the hell out of everybody . '' <br><blue>18</blue>Mr. Hardy said , '' You 're on . '' <br><blue>19</blue>Guided by the director , the author rewrote half the play , including the ending . <br><blue>20</blue>In fact , there were so many changes that the production itself became a cliffhanger . <br><hr><br><blue>1(2)</blue>: <m_str>Regis High School in Manhattan and Fordham University</m_str> (9_11) 	<m_str>his school</m_str> (11_17) 	<br><blue>2(2)</blue>: <m_str>Child 's Play</m_str> (11_3) 	<m_str>Child 's Play</m_str> (1_15) 	<br><blue>3(2)</blue>: <m_str>Manhasset , N.Y.</m_str> (1_29) 	<m_str>N.Y.</m_str> (2_10) 	<br><blue>4(2)</blue>: <m_str>the work</m_str> (11_26) 	<m_str>It</m_str> (12_1) 	<br><blue>5(2)</blue>: <m_str>Mr. Howard</m_str> (7_5) 	<m_str>Ken Howard</m_str> (6_8) 	<br><blue>6(6)</blue>: <m_str>the play</m_str> (8_9) 	<m_str>the play</m_str> (10_9) 	<m_str>the play</m_str> (16_19) 	<m_str>it</m_str> (17_5) 	<m_str>the play</m_str> (14_8) 	<m_str>half the play</m_str> (19_9) 	<br><blue>7(3)</blue>: <m_str>He</m_str> (2_1) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (3_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (3_8) 	<br><blue>8(4)</blue>: <m_str>Mr. Hardy</m_str> (18_1) 	<m_str>Joseph Hardy for his direction and Jo Mielziner</m_str> (7_13) 	<m_str>You</m_str> (18_6) 	<m_str>Mr. Hardy</m_str> (16_9) 	<br><blue>9(2)</blue>: <m_str>his director</m_str> (16_5) 	<m_str>the director</m_str> (19_3) 	<br><blue>10(2)</blue>: <m_str>the author and his director</m_str> (16_2) 	<m_str>the author</m_str> (19_6) 	<br><blue>11(2)</blue>: <m_str>itself</m_str> (20_12) 	<m_str>the production</m_str> (20_10) 	<br><blue>12(13)</blue>: <m_str>he</m_str> (11_10) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (7_16) 	<m_str>Mr. Merrick</m_str> (15_8) 	<m_str>Mr. Merrick</m_str> (8_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (11_17) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (11_20) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (12_4) 	<m_str>Mr. Marasco</m_